      <p>Annerley sits on the Ipswich Road corridor in Brisbane's inner south, roughly four kilometres from the CBD. It borders Dutton Park to the north, Fairfield to the west, and Greenslopes to the east, which means it shares school catchments and city access with suburbs that have been repricing strongly. For a long time Annerley traded at a discount to those neighbours, but that gap has been closing as buyers who find Dutton Park and Fairfield beyond reach move further along the corridor. Sellers in Annerley are now operating in a more active market than the suburb's historical reputation might suggest.</p>

      <p>The housing stock is predominantly pre-war and post-war character: timber Queenslanders and fibro homes on relatively generous blocks, mixed with a growing number of properties that have been renovated or extended in recent years. The suburb has a genuine residential identity separate from the commercial noise of Ipswich Road, and the streets that run off the main arterial retain a quieter, more established feel than the corridor itself would imply.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Annerley</h2>
      <p>First home buyers and couples upsizing from inner-city units are the most active buyer segment, drawn by the suburb's relative affordability and city proximity. Young families who have been priced out of Greenslopes and Coorparoo are also present, particularly for homes that sit within the preferred school catchments. A consistent investor segment exists given the suburb's rental demand from university and hospital workers, though the dominant profile at the upper end of the market is owner-occupier. Buyers here have generally done their research and understand how Annerley compares to its neighbours.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Annerley</h2>
      <p>Distance from Ipswich Road is the primary location variable: homes on the quieter streets east of the main road, particularly those with good separation from traffic noise, consistently outperform similar homes on or adjacent to the arterial. Character integrity is a meaningful driver at the upper end of the market. Original Queenslanders with retained features, including VJ walls, timber floors, wide verandahs and high ceilings, attract a buyer who is specifically seeking that typology and will pay a premium over a comparable renovated fibro home. Block size and the potential for future improvement or subdivision are factors that attract both owner-occupiers and investors at the development-aware end of the market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale</h2>
      <p>Annerley buyers range from first home buyers with limited renovation capacity to experienced buyers who actively seek unrenovated stock. Understanding which segment your property is targeting shapes the preparation strategy. For homes aimed at owner-occupiers who intend to live in the property, ensuring it presents as clean, maintained and move-in ready is the baseline investment. For character homes with original features, the priority is showcasing those features rather than concealing them with inappropriate cosmetic updates. Fresh paint in period-appropriate colours, clean floors and a tidy garden are the fundamentals that apply regardless of which buyer segment you are targeting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Annerley has a broad enough buyer pool to support auction for well-positioned homes, particularly those with character architecture or strong land content. The buyer spillover from Dutton Park and Fairfield means that a well-run auction campaign can attract buyers who are searching across multiple inner-south suburbs simultaneously. Private treaty works better for properties with a more defined appeal, such as those primarily targeting investors or buyers with a specific development intent. In both cases, the price needs to be set with reference to comparable sales in Dutton Park, Fairfield and Greenslopes, not only within Annerley itself. Buyers are comparing across that corridor and will identify pricing that is out of step with the broader market.</p>


      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Annerley</h2>
      <p>Annerley's strongest selling windows sit in spring (September to November) and autumn (March to May). Spring activates the first-home-buyer segment that is most active in Annerley: buyers who have been saving through winter and want to be settled before the end of the year. The autumn window captures buyers who missed out in spring and have reset their search with greater urgency. Annerley benefits from spillover demand from Dutton Park and Fairfield throughout both seasons — buyers searching those suburbs have Annerley on their shortlist and will move quickly on well-priced stock. One suburb-specific factor worth noting is the Ipswich Road upgrade corridor: properties that are not directly affected by road widening notices tend to attract stronger competition, and buyers researching those questions are most active mid-year when planning announcements tend to land.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Annerley</h2>
      <p>Well-priced Annerley homes typically move in 28 to 38 days under current conditions. The suburb draws buyers from a wide inner-south catchment — Dutton Park, Fairfield, Greenslopes — which means a well-positioned campaign has a deep enough pool to generate competition without relying on a single buyer segment. Properties on the quieter streets east of Ipswich Road tend to move faster than those adjacent to the arterial, where noise concerns extend buyer decision timelines. Character Queenslanders with intact original features hold above-average interest across the full campaign because they attract a buyer who is specifically seeking that typology; fibro homes aimed at renovators attract a narrower pool and typically need more days to locate the right buyer. Overpriced stock lingers: Annerley buyers understand how the suburb compares to Dutton Park and Fairfield and will not overpay for what they can get closer to the city.</p>

